While it's true that Louis DeJoy has plans to reduce USPS positions, it's not a direct job cut but rather a reduction through voluntary early retirements and expected attrition over the next few years. The number of positions to be reduced represents only a quarter of the attrition the agency expects to see over a similar period. DeJoy has also stated that USPS will remain in a hiring posture in the coming years. As for why DeJoy still holds his position, the Postmaster General is not a political appointee and cannot be removed by a president. This tweet is potentially misleading. A period, or menstrual cycle, is a biological process that involves the shedding of the uterine lining when an egg is not fertilized. It is not merely a state of mind. Ovulation, the release of a mature egg from an ovary, is a key part of this process. If the egg is not fertilized, it is expelled from the body during menstruation. Transgender women, while deserving of respect and inclusivity, do not have the biological capacity to menstruate or ovulate as they do not have ovaries or a uterus. Therefore, they cannot have periods in the biological sense. However, they may experience symptoms similar to premenstrual syndrome due to hormone therapy.

This tweet is somewhat misleading. While Biden did campaign on forgiving undergraduate tuition-related federal student loan debt for certain borrowers, including those from public colleges and HBCUs earning up to $125,000 per year, he did not promise to cancel *all* federal student debt for these groups. He pledged to cancel at least $10,000 of student debt per person and has since acted on these plans, with the Education Department discharging or in the process of discharging roughly $12.7 billion in student debt. However, Biden's approach to student loan relief began with improving, extending, or expanding existing programs, not widespread debt cancellation.

While it's true that the time period from 2015-2022 represents a small fraction of manmade CO2 contribution, it's incorrect to suggest that climate change is a hoax based on this short-term data. Climate change is a long-term trend, and short-term fluctuations do not negate the overall warming trend. The World Meteorological Organization confirms that the past decade was the hottest on record (https://public.wmo.int/en/media/press-release/2020-was-one-of-three-warmest-years-record). Furthermore, NASA's data shows a clear long-term global warming trend (https://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/global-temperature/).

This tweet is misleading. While it's true that 2022 may not be the warmest year on record due to a rare triple-dip cooling La Niña, this doesn't reverse the long-term warming trend. The 10-year average for 2013-2022 is estimated to be 1.14°C above the pre-industrial baseline, compared to 1.09°C from 2011 to 2020. The last eight years have been unusually warm, exceeding 1.2C above pre-industrial levels. The long-term warming since the industrial revolution is attributable to increased concentrations of CO2 and other greenhouse gases. Looking at data over a short period in isolation can lead to misleading conclusions. The impacts of climate change, such as record ocean heat levels and rising sea levels, are becoming more dramatic.

https://www.carbonbrief.org/factcheck-no-global-warming-has-not-paused-over-the-past-eight-years/
